h3. Summary

When creating a page via a REST call, if the storage format has an attachment, then that attachment is lost on subsequent edits of the page via the UI, even though it displays correctly on first view.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page via REST call with an embedded attachment (here, an image)
{code:java|title=create page}
curl -s -u admin:admin -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"type":"page","title":"my page","space":{"key":"KEY"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>This is a new page</p><p><ac:image ac:thumbnail=\"true\" ac:height=\"250\"><ri:attachment ri:filename=\"meeple.png\" /></ac:image></p>","representation":"storage"}}}' http://localhost:8090/rest/api/content/
{code}

 # Upload the attachment (change page id as required)
{code:java|title=upload attachment}
curl -s -u admin:admin -H "X-Atlassian-Token: no-check" -F "file=@meeple.png" -F "comment=this is my meeple" "http://localhost:8090/rest/api/content/327714/child/attachment"{code}

 # Edit the page through the browser to make a change.

h3. Expected Results

The image stays attached to the page and displays correctly.

!expected.png|thumbnail!
h3. Actual Results

The image appears as a *Broken Attachment* both in view and edit

[^actual.png]
h3. Workaround

Create the page with dummy content, upload the attachment and then update the page with the correct content.
{code:java|title=create page}
curl -s -u admin:admin -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"type":"page","title":"my page","space":{"key":"KEY"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>This is a page holder</p>","representation":"storage"}}}' http://localhost:8090/rest/api/content/
{code}
{code:java|title=upload attachment}
curl -s -u admin:admin -H "X-Atlassian-Token: no-check" -F "file=@meeple.png" -F "comment=this is my meeple" "http://localhost:8090/rest/api/content/327714/child/attachment"
{code}
{code:java|title=update page content}
curl -s -u admin:admin -X PUT -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"id":"327714","type":"page","title":"my page",
"body":{"storage":{"value":
"<p>This is a new page</p><p><ac:image ac:thumbnail=\"true\" ac:height=\"250\"><ri:attachment ri:filename=\"meeple.png\" /></ac:image></p>","representation":"storage"}},"version":{"number":2}}' http://localhost:8090/rest/api/content/327714
{code}

When viewing Confluence from a iPad we are presented with:

"You're viewing the desktop version on a mobile device. Switch to Confluence mobile"

We would like the ability to turn off this messaging.

Screenshot:
 !image-2018-10-29-18-57-54-641.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround

The steps below are only applicable to *Confluence Server (Data Center)*:

# Go to *Cog Icon* > *General Configuration* > *Custom HTML*
# Click on *Edit*.
# Add the following script *At end of the BODY*:
{code}
<script type="text/javascript">
    AJS.toInit(function(){
	  AJS.$('.confluence-messages.infoMessage').hide();
    });
</script>
{code}
# Click on *Save*.
# Your configuration will look like as below.
 !custom_html.png|thumbnail!

h2. Problem Definition

Currently when the Companion App MSI file is deployed by admins wishing to roll out this feature to multiple Windows machines the app still needs to be manually started before it can make the system call to add it to launch at startup. Customers have run into this issue and see that only after running the app manually the registry entry is placed here: {{HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run}}

This differs from the normal installer behaviour (.exe) which does launch the Companion App after installing. However, MSIs are usually installed via an admin account, so having the executable launch automatically after installation will not solve the problem (as this will only add the registry entry for the admin user). 
h3. Current scenario:

After user runs the App for the first time, the registry key will be added in the following path
{noformat}
HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run{noformat}
h2. Workaround:

The registry key can be added to HKCU (for all users that should have Companion running) during the deployment to ensure that the app is started automatically without having the user to start it manually.

For 32-bit OS:
{code:java}
msiexec /qn /i "Atlassian Companion.msi"
reg add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run" /v "electron.app.Atlassian Companion" /d "C:\Program Files\Atlassian Companion\Atlassian Companion.exe --was-opened-at-login" /f
{code}
For 64-bit OS:
{code:java}
msiexec /qn /i "Atlassian Companion.msi"
reg add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run" /v "electron.app.Atlassian Companion" /d "C:\Program Files (x86)\Atlassian Companion\Atlassian Companion.exe --was-opened-at-login" /f
{code}
 

As of Companion 0.6.0, a registry key can alternatively be manually added to HKLM (instead of HKCU) with no side effects. This will allow Companion to automatically launch for all users on the machine. The process will be the same as above, but adding the registry key to HKLM: 

{{HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\WOW6432Node\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run}}

h3. Problem Definition
Confluence will retrieve a full 404 page when a restricted content is requested from a mail client, which is an inefficient operation since the content retrieved will not be rendered by the client.

The problem is detailed below:
Users may add Confluence content (such as images) into an e-mail.
This content will be fetched by the e-mail client, such as MS Outlook, and Confluence will retrieve it.
One can simulate the e-mail client request by running a {{GET}} operation with curl similar to the one below:
{code}
curl -u user:user -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; MSIE 9.0; Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/7.0; Microsoft Outlook 15.0.5059; ms-office; MSOffice 15)' -H 'Accept: */*' -H 'Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.5' 'http://localhost:8080/c663/download/thumbnails/9076744/image_name.png?version=1&modificationDate=1541779552344&api=v2' -H 'Pragma: no-cache' -H 'Cache-Control: no-cache'
{code}

If the user that received the e-mail doesn't have access to this content, Confluence will retrieve a full 404 page, on the same way as accessing it from the browser.
See below an example of the response:
 !request_curl_img001.png|thumbnail! 

This isn't efficient, since Confluence will go through the whole process to build all components of the 404 page, which will not be used by the client.
As an example, Confluence will build the top bar, which requires permissions validation to determine which components will be rendered to the user.
These permissions validation are costly operations to Confluence and could be avoided in the above scenario.

h3. Suggested Solution
If the user agent of the current request is MS Outlook ([contains the string {{Microsoft Outlook}}|https://udger.com/resources/ua-list/browser-detail?browser=Outlook%202016]), then Confluence should send only a 404 status without retrieving any page content.
The same could be applied when the user agent is any other email client.

h3. Performance Impact on Scale
Fixing this bug would help Confluence to be more efficient, retrieving a full 404 page only when needed -- i.e. user accessing it from a browser.
On scale, an e-mail with a restricted image can be sent to several recipients that don't have access to it. Serving a full 404 page to thousands of users is costly to Confluence and to the Database.
In depth:
 * Building the top bar requires Confluence to check for permissions, which is a costly operation.
 * Running thousands of queries in the database may consume too much of RAM, provided that these queries will use a {{join}} operation.

Depending on the size of your Confluence instance, this could create a situation on which around 10,000 of GET requests would be sent to Confluence from e-mail clients.

h3. Workaround
If you are running Confluence behind a proxy, you could create a filter to drop requests from an e-mail client when a burst is detected.
The configuration below is based on [Nginx Rate Limiting|https://www.nginx.com/blog/rate-limiting-nginx/] to drop requests for images from an MS Outlook client after a burst.
You may need to change the threshold according to your environment. Also, other proxy technologies may offer similar capabilities.
{code:title=Nginx Rate Limiting example}
### filter for requests coming from an Outlook client
map $http_user_agent $bad_outlook {
    default "";
    ~*(Outlook) 1;
}
limit_req_zone $bad_outlook zone=outlook:10m rate=10r/m;
limit_req_status 429;
server {
    ### your standard Confluence configuration


    ### use Outlook filter on thumbnails
    location ^~ /c663/download/thumbnails {
        limit_req zone=outlook;
        proxy_pass http://localhost:6663/c663/download/thumbnails;
    }
    ### use Outlook filter on attachments
    location ^~ /c663/download/attachments {
        limit_req zone=outlook;
        proxy_pass http://localhost:6663/c663/download/attachments;
    }
}
{code}

h3. Summary

No printout of numbered headings using CSS in PDF exports.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

e.g. enter in Settings -> Design -> Global (CSS)Style Template:
h1:before {
content: counter(ebene1, upper-roman)". ";
counter-increment: ebene1;}
h1 {counter-reset: ebene2;}
h2:before {
content: counter(ebene2)". ";
counter-increment: ebene2;}
h2 {counter-reset: ebene3;}
h3:before {
content: counter(ebene3, lower-latin)". ";
counter-increment: ebene3;}

h3. Expected Results

The numbered headings, which show on the page, are also shown on the PDF exports.

h3. Actual Results

The numbering of the headings is displayed correctly in the view mode of the viewer - when printing the page with the PDF option these numberings of the headings are missing in the PDF document, i.e. the numbers and letters of the numbering are not transferred to the PDF document. But with normal printing with a paper printer, these numberings are printed out completely correctly. 

But unfortunately there is the following problem when printing with a paper printer.

h3.Workaround

There is no workaround.

h3. Summary

If you e.g. enter in Settings -> Design -> Global (CSS) Style Template:

{code}h2 { font: 1.4em Georgia,serif;
letter-spacing: 5px;
font-weight: bright;
text-align: left;
color: rgb(255,102,0);
background: #RRGGBB;
padding-left: -10em;
repeat-x 0 0%;}{code}


h3. Steps to Reproduce

See above.

h3. Expected Results

The text is colored.

h3. Actual Results

The h2 heading is displayed in "edit mode" with the correct color, but not in the "normal" view mode of the viewer. Even if you specify another color instead of the RGB color, e.g. "color: FF 63 47;" or "color: #00FF00;" or "color: green;", the color is not displayed in the viewer's view mode.
 
h3.Workaround

There is no workaround.
